0.body: This tiny book serves as a summary of most of the stuff that I've studied during the course " Algorithmen und Datenstrukturen " at ETHZ. The course is in German but the exam is in English: this often leads to confusion, as everything that gets taught during the lectures has to be translated in English by the students themselves. While it might be an easy task for a native german speaker, I can assure you that it gets harder for students that don't speak the language every day. The whole lesson would be: Hear the professor teaching about something in German Look up the word / term / ... on the internet and look for a translation in English. Rethink about what has been said in English, so you won't get completely destroyed by terms you don't know in the exam. No cheatsheet is allowed there, thus remembering every definition, every technical term, how every datastructure or algorithm works is a hard task. Having a small book that contains all information needed in a readable way is a great way to prepare yourself for that very tragic day. Repetition is the key, the more the better. Note that this isn't meant as your only source of information during your studies: I might make mistakes while writing this and I'm pretty sure that I'm not the best teacher there is. I'm not Abdul :(

15.body: There are various ways to search a data structure. Here we analyze ways to search an array. The fastest method depends on the properties of said array.
15.title: Search Algorithms

16.body: Time: O(n) The simplest method. Simply iterate through the array and compare every element with the one you're looking for. For example, let's say that we want to find out k's index in the array A. If k is not in the array, we should get -1 as a result. The following procedure does exactly that: Initialize i = 0 If A's length is less or equal i, return -1. If A[i] == k, return i. Increment i Go to step 1 .
16.title: Linear Search

17.body: Time: O(logn) Sometimes we need to search a value in a sorted array, meaning that ∀i∀j (i<j⇒A[i]≤A[j]) An array could also be sorted in descending order. The same search method can be easily adapted for such case. The procedure to search for k in said array A is the following: Initialize l = 0 and r = A.length - 1. Set mid = (l + r) / 2. If mid is not a valid index for A, return -1 (not found). Compare k with A[mid]. If k is greater, then set l = mid + 1. If k is smaller, then set r = mid - 1. Else, we've found k. Return mid. At every step, half of the remaining items are excluded from the search: thus the logaritmic time.
17.title: Binary Search

2.body: A tree is a structure that begins from a root. Each node a can have a child node b. We can say then that a is the parent of b and b is a child of a. There are various types of tree. Every parent can have a certain amount of children, depending on the type of tree. The nodes that have no children ("the bottom-most ones") are called leaves .
2.title: Tree

20.body: Best Average Worst Time O(n) O(n2) O(n2) Space (aux) O(1) O(1) O(1) Procedure: Set i = 0 Iterate from i to the end of the array Set j = i If A[j] > A[j + 1] swap the two values increment j and repeat step 5 if A has a j-th element. Otherwise, increment i and go to step 2 Can be optimized to stop if the sequence is already sorted (checking if any value was swapped in the last run). However, the average and worst case remains unchanged.
20.title: Bubble Sort

21.body: Best Average Worst Comparisons O(n2) O(n2) O(n2) Swaps O(1) O(n) O(n) Space (aux) O(1) O(1) O(1) Procedure: Set i = 0. Find the min value from i to the end of the array. Swap it with the element at index i. Increment i, go to step 2 .
21.title: Selection Sort

22.body: Best Average Worst Comparisons O(n) O(n2) O(n2) Swaps O(1) O(n2) O(n2) Space (aux) O(1) O(1) O(1) Procedure: Set i = 1. Insert A[i] in the sequence to its left, so that it is sorted. Increment i and go to step 2 . Note that step 2 can be made faster by using binary search .
22.title: Insertion Sort

23.body: This sort makes use of a max-heap to sort the values. Best Average Worst Time O(nlogn) O(nlogn) O(nlogn) Space (aux) O(1) O(1) O(1) Procedure: Build the max heap with count elements. Swap the biggest value (first value) of A and the one at index count - 1. Decrease count Repair the heap ( the element that was inserted in the back isn't part of the heap anymore! ). Go to step 2 . For steps 1 and 4 see Datastructures
23.title: Heap Sort

24.body: This sort is a divide-and-conquer approach. It uses extra memory. Best Average Worst Time O(nlogn) O(nlogn) O(nlogn) Space (aux) O(n) O(n) O(n) It consists in sorting a subarray, then merging two sorted subarrays. This way it obtains a longer sorted subarray. It keeps merging until the final array is obtained. The algorithm is composed of two procedures: Let A be the array to be sorted and B be the auxiliary array (same size as A). Merge (given two subarrays at idx a to b - 1 and from b to end): Initialize k = a, i = a, j = b. If k >= end return. If i < b and (A[i] <= A[j] or j >= end), then assign B[k] = A[i] and increment i. Else, assign B[k] = A[j] and increment j. Go to step 1 . In short, this procedure compares the elements (starting from the begining) of the two subarrays and inserts the minimum in B. If j >= end or i >= b, then one of the two subarrays has "run out of elements", thus the remaining elements are inserted last. Now the rest of the procedure: Merge Sort an array A: Initialize B with the same length as A. Initialize width = 1. Initialize i = 0. Merge the subarrays i to i + width - 1 and i + width to i + 2 * width. All of these indices are rounded down to fit the length of the array. Set i = i + 2 * width. If i is a valid index for the array, go to step 3 . Set width = 2 * width. If width is less than the length of the array, go to step 2 . This is a bottom-up solution: it starts merging subarrays of single elements to form sorted subarrays of two elements. Then it merges these 2-length subarrays into 4 element-long subarrays. At every iteration it has to process n elements and it does so O(logn) times. Thus the running time of O(nlogn).
24.title: Merge Sort

26.body: A graph is composed of vertices and edges . G=(V,E),v∈V,e∈E A graph can be undirected or directed : In an undirected graph, an edge e=(u,v) is a two-way connection between two vertices. In a directed graph, the edge e=(u,v) is a one-way connection, from vertex u to v. A graph can be weighted . In this case, G=(V,E,w) and w: E→W is a function that maps an edge to its cost c∈W. Some useful terminology: Walk : Trail : Path :
26.title: Graphs

27.body: The idea is to discover the graph by starting at a vertex s and then traversing the children depth-first. A recursive procedure for DFS starting at vertex s could be this: label s as discovered For all edges (s, v) do: If vertex v is not discovered, run DFS with v as source.

31.body: Runtime with binary heap: O((∣V∣+∣E∣)log∣V∣) Runtime with Fibonacci Heap: O(∣E∣+∣V∣log∣V∣) The version using a binary heap uses a priority queue (min-heap). It only works with non-negative weights! Given a graph G and a source s, the procedure is the following: Initialize two arrays with one entry per vertex: distance[v] = +INF and parent[v] = null. Initialize a priority queue (min-heap). Set distance[s] = 0 Add s to the queue with key 0. if the queue is empty, return. extract the min value u from the queue. For every edge (u, v), do the following: if v has no parent, set u as its parent and set distance[v] = distance[u] + w(u, v) else if distance[v] > distance[u] + w(u, v), change v's parent to u and set its new distance. Then change v's key in the queue to its new distance. Go to step 4
31.title: Dijkstra's algorithm

32.breadcrumbs: Graphs » Shortest Paths between all pairs
32.title: Shortest Paths between all pairs

33.body: Time: Θ(∣V∣3) Space: Θ(∣V∣2) This algorithm uses dynamic programming to compute the shortest path between pairs. It does not work with negative cycles, altough it can detect them easily. Let's represent the data in a matrix D, where every row and column correspond to a vertex v1​,v2​,...,vn​. The base case is, given a row i and a column j: ⎩⎪⎪⎨⎪⎪⎧​Di,j​=0Di,j​=w(vi​,vj​)Di,j​=∞​if i=jif ∃(vi​,vj​)∈Eotherwise ​ In plain text, the base case is: 0 if on the diagonal (i=j) w(vi​,vj​) if there's an edge (vi​,vj​) ∞ otherwise The next step is to iterate a total of ∣V∣3 times, with the following recursive case, sp(i,j,k)=min(sp(i,j,k−1),sp(i,k,k−1)+sp(k,j,k−1)) where sp(i,j,k) is the shortest path between vertices i and j and "middle vertex" k. The full procedure is: Initialize the ∣V∣×∣V∣ table D, filled with ∞ For each edge (u, v), set D[u][v] = w(u, v) For each vertex v set D[v][v] = 0 For k in 1 to ∣V∣: For i in 1 to ∣V∣ For j in 1 to ∣V∣ If D[i][j] <= D[i][k] + D[k][j], do nothing. Otherwise, set the new shortest path D[i][j] = D[i][k] + D[k][j]. After the execution, D will contain the shortest path between every pair of vertices, unless there's a negative cycle in the graph. In that case there's gonna be negative values along the diagonal, where only zeros are to be expected. If there's negative values along the diagonal, then there's a negative cycle and the result is incorrect.
33.title: Floyd-Warshall algorithm

34.body: Time (worst case): O(∣V∣2log∣V∣+∣V∣∣E∣) This algorithm uses both the Bellman-Ford and Dijkstra's algorithms to find the shortest path between every pair of vertices. It works by adding a vertex q into the graph, connected to every vertex by a 0-weight edge . Then the Bellman-Ford algorithm is executed (starting from q) to find for each vertex the minimum weight h(v) of a path from q to v. If this step detects a negative cycle, the algorithm stops. It then reweights the edges of the original graph: the edge (u,v) is given the new length w(u,v)+h(u)−h(v) Finally, q is removed and Dijkstra's algorithm is ran on each node s to find the shortest path between it and the other nodes. After this, h(v)−h(u) is re-added to Dijkstra's result to obtain the shortest path on the original graph. Procedure: Add a vertex q to the graph and add a 0-weight edge (q, v) for every v. Run the Bellman-Ford algorithm from q to find the minimum weight h(v) of a path from q to v. Change the weight of every edge, by setting it to w(u, v) + h(u) - h(v) Remove q from the graph Run Dijkstra on every vertex s to obtain the shortest path between every s and the other vertices. We now have the distances D(u, v). Add h(v) - h(u) to every distance D(u, v) to obtain the length of the shortest path between every pair of vertices.
34.title: Johnson's algorithm

36.body: Time: O(∣E∣log∣V∣) The idea is to first divide the graph in one-vertex components. Then the cheapest edge connecting every component to another component is found and added to the MST. The components are then joined. Procedure: Initialize ∣V∣ components, each one containing one vertex. Also initialize a list that will contain the edges of the MST. If there's less than two components, return. For each component, find the lowest weight edge that connects it to another component. Then add this edge to the MST and connect the two components. Go to step 1 .
36.title: Boruvka's algorithm

37.body: Time (binary heap): O((∣V∣+∣E∣)log∣V∣)≤O(∣E∣log∣V∣) Prim' algorithm requires a starting vertex s. Procedure:
37.title: Prim's algorithm

38.body: Time: O(∣E∣log∣V∣) This algorithm requires a disjoin-set data structure. It is similar to Boruvka's, but it differs in the fact that instead of looking for the cheapest edge of every component, it looks for the cheapest edge that connects any two components. Procedure: Intialize a list for the edges of the MST. Let E be the list of edges of the graph, sorted by increasing weight. Create a set for each vertex in the graph. For each edge (u, v) in E do: If u and v are in the same set, continue. Otherwise, add the edge (u, v) in the MST and perform an union operation on u's and v's sets. Note: to prove the running time, ∣E∣≤∣V∣2⇒O(log∣E∣)≤O(log∣V∣)
38.title: Kruskal's algorithm

4.body: A binary search tree is a tree where every node has two children: a left one and a right one. For every node p, these conditions hold: Every node of the left subtree of p (the left child and all its descendants) has a value less or equal the one of p. Every node of the right subtree of p has a value greater or equal the one of p. This way it's possible to look for an element in O(logn) time. Search for a key k: If the tree is empty, return. Set the current node as the root If the current node is null, then the node is not in the tree. Return. If the current node is greater than k, set its left child as current node. Then go back to step 2. Else, if the current node is less than k, set its right child as current node. Then go to step 2. Else, it means that the current node is equal to k. The node has been found, return.
4.title: Binary Search Tree

6.body: A min / max heap os a type of binary tree where a condition must hold: In a min / max heap, every parent is smaller / greater than all of its children. It can be conveniently represented in memory as an array (0-indexed), where a node at index i has left child 2*i + 1 and right child 2*i + 2. This way it's easy to traverse the heap. Sift Up Time: O(logn) Starts at a given element. Check if the condition holds for this element and its parent If not, swap the two. If it does, stop. Now this element is in a different place. Go back to step 1 . Sift Down Time: O(logn) For an element x: Get the max between x, its right child and its left one. If x is not the max, swap the max with x. Otherwise, stop. x is in a different place now. Go back to step 1. Insert Time: O(logn) To insert a value in said heap, the most common way is to add it to the end of the array. Then perform a " sift up " operation on that element. Extract Time: O(logn) Remove the root and put the last leaf of the heap in its place. Then perform the " sift down " operation on the new root. Build a min / max heap There are two ways to build said heap. Insert each element one by one in time O(nlogn)=n⋅O(logn) Perform the heapify operation on the given array (used in the HeapSort sorting algorithm). The first way is too easy, so uninteresting. The second way ( heapify ) uses the sift down operation to transform the array in an heap. Procedure "Heapify": For every index i from the end of the array to the start, do: Sift Down i That's it. This is gonna build a heap from an array in-place (O(1) auxiliary space) and in time O(n). Why time O(n)? Well, the number of operations of sift down depends on how close we're to the bottom. Since we start at the bottom, the sift down operation on the leaves runs no operations. Thus the total number of calls of "sift down" is gonna be 02n​+14n​+28n​+316n​+...=ni=2∑∞​​(i−1)2i1​≤ni=1∑∞​​2i1​≤O(n)
6.title: Min / Max heap
